# Aero Engine — LeakSanitizer suppressions (task 0.4.2, spec D16: evidence-gated, never pre-seeded).
#
# Scope: wired ONLY into the Debug ctest step's LSAN_OPTIONS for Linux (.github/workflows/ci.yml) —
# the one lane where LSan runs. First-party leak detection stays fully ON: every entry below names a
# specific THIRD-PARTY allocation origin observed on the first GPU-backed CI run (PR #16, run
# 29599267631). There, doctest reported 227/227 SUCCESS and LSan then flagged ~3.1 MB in 57,584
# allocations, all rooted in SDL3's x11 video-driver init and SDL_GPU's Vulkan probe
# (lavapipe/loader frames) — zero allocation sites in engine/ or tests/ code; engine frames appear
# only as mid-stack call sites (Context::Context -> SDL_Init, Device::create ->
# SDL_CreateGPUDeviceWithProperties). Surfaced now because 0.4.2's gated tests are the first thing
# on this lane to init a REAL video driver (x11 under Xvfb); the pre-0.4.2 suite was dummy-driver
# only and never touched these paths.
#
# Rules for this file (spec D16): add an entry ONLY with observed CI evidence, one commented entry
# per observed frame; never suppress module-wide (e.g. leak:SDL) — that would blind LSan to real
# engine leaks whose allocations happen inside SDL (a forgotten SDL_ReleaseGPU* would allocate
# under SDL_CreateGPUBuffer et al., which stay unsuppressed).
#
# The two lavapipe entries at the bottom (leak:libvulkan_lvp, leak:libLLVM) are deliberate,
# narrowly-justified exceptions to "never module-wide". They are admissible where leak:SDL is not,
# for two reasons: (1) their leak frames NEVER symbolize to a function/source name — the driver
# stack is unmapped before exit, so the module path is the ONLY matchable token (see those entries
# and tests/vulkan_stack_pin.cpp); and (2) they do not create a realistic first-party blind spot:
# every engine GPU resource is pool-tracked and released by ~Device before LSan runs (the "~Device
# releasing N leaked ..." safety net), so no engine leak survives inside the driver at exit, and
# CPU-side engine leaks never touch these modules at all (leak:libLLVM in particular can only ever
# match Mesa's shader-codegen backend, which no engine allocation path reaches). If a future
# dbgsym-enabled run yields the specific worker-thread FUNCTION name, tighten to that name and drop
# the module scope.

# SDL3's x11 video driver retains keyboard/XKB tables per init cycle (SDL_x11keyboard.c:166/:177).
leak:X11_InitKeyboard
# SDL3's x11 video init retains XRandR mode / content-scale data (SDL_x11modes.c, reached from
# X11_VideoInit, SDL_x11video.c:448 — this entry covers those stacks via any-frame matching).
leak:X11_VideoInit
# SDL_GPU's Vulkan backend probe retains loader/lavapipe allocations from instance/physical-device
# enumeration (SDL_gpu_vulkan.c:12362/:12709), reached via both VULKAN_PrepareDriver and
# VULKAN_CreateDevice.
leak:VULKAN_INTERNAL_DeterminePhysicalDevice
leak:VULKAN_INTERNAL_PrepareVulkan

# Mesa/lavapipe worker-thread pool (task 0.5.2). The first texture-sampling fragment shader the cube
# test compiles+runs spins up a fixed lavapipe pool (one thread per core = 4 on the CI runner); each
# worker calloc's a ~56-byte per-thread struct never freed at exit (224 B / 4 allocations). NOT the
# rasterizer pool (LP_NUM_THREADS=0 left the count unchanged, run 29679720635) and NOT the disk-cache
# writer pool (MESA_SHADER_CACHE_DISABLE likewise, run 29680407602) — a different, non-disableable
# pool. SDL loads/UNLOADS libvulkan.so.1 per Device lifecycle, and this Ubuntu loader unmaps the ICD
# (libvulkan_lvp.so) + its libLLVM with it, so by teardown they read <unknown module> at LSan-time;
# LD_PRELOAD to keep them mapped is impossible (aborts the ASan runtime), and pinning only the loader
# did not stop the ICD unmap (run 29681929403). So tests/vulkan_stack_pin.cpp dlopens the ICD ITSELF
# with RTLD_NODELETE IN-PROCESS — that mapping then survives every dlclose, so the frames resolve to
# real module names and these two entries match (LSan matches suppressions against function/file/
# module names). The pool lives in libvulkan_lvp.so and/or its libLLVM codegen backend (the leak split
# across two load bases with identical offsets); both are covered — a still-red run would NAME the true
# module in the log. Runs 29679001505 / 29679720635 / 29680407602 / 29681071731 / 29681929403. See the
# module-wide-exception rationale in the header.
leak:libvulkan_lvp
leak:libLLVM
